Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

Notes: Shape, Data Types, Statistics¶

  • There are 3,454 entries, and 15 descriptors.
  • The data has 4 categories as object/strings: 4g, 5g, Brand Name and OS. These will likely serve as grouping techniques.
  • 4g and 5g are categorical, and will be converted to Dummies as we prepare.
  • The release year can help with grouping devices. It is listed as numeric but we can utilize it as a categorical variable. We can enhance this data feature to know the age of a phone by comparing it to when it was collecged (2021, see Problem Statement)

  • As per the problem statement, the 'normalized_used_price' will serve as the dependent variable when we reach regression calculations.

  • The average used_price and new_price of phones are closely related. This means that phones sold through ReCell have a close relationship to their original price when they were new.

  • Phones have been used from 91 to 1,094 days; less than a year to around 3 years.
  • It is interesting to note that a singular phone can be listed as having 4g and 5g (example: rows 1, 2, 3). This predictor may have multi-collinearity as we work with preparing our data for regression.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of normalized used device prices look like?
  2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?
  3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  4. A large battery often increases a device's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones and tablets offering large batteries (more than 4500 mAh)?
  5. Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones and tablets are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  6. A lot of devices nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of devices offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the normalized price of a used device?

#function for boxplots and histograms
def box_hist(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram

    data: dataframe
    feature: desired column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (set to True)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function for barplots

def labeled_bar(data, feature, perc=True, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: desired column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (set to True)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

If outliers exist, we will check if they heavily impact the data (outrageous values). Else, they will be considered proper values.

  • int_memory has a large value of 1000. however, a quick online search will tell you that phones with 1TB of memory do exist on the market, we will not delete this from our data.
  • The outliers seen for main_camera_mp and selfie_camera_mp are similar and not ridiculously large, we will not remove them from our data as they are proper values. -Overall, we will not treat any outliers in the data as they are proper for the market of phones/tablets from many years of technology advancements.

Data Prep¶

Problem Statement asks for prediction of Normalized Used Price of cell phones for the ReCell company.

  • Dependent Variable (y) = normalized_used_price

  • Independent Variables (x) = os, 4g/5g, main_camera_mp, selfie_camera_mp, int_memory, ram, battery, weight, days_used, normalized_new_price

    Note: Os and 4g, 5g are categorical variables. We will need to make dummy variables. We will have a column that describes yes/no for OS as well as 4G vs 5G.

In [43]:

Model Performance Check¶

In [52]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))

# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100
In [53]:
# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_performance = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_performance

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

  • In order to make statistical inferences from a linear regression model, it is important to ensure that the assumptions of linear regression are satisfied.

Assumptions to check:

  1. Multicollinearity (routinely check VIF and p-values). To remove correlation between two or more independent variables, we will drop one variable at a time as needed.
  2. Linearity / Independence (compare plot of fitted vs residuals). To deal with non-linearity, we may transofrm variables as per their relationship to the dependent variable. We will take this course of action if our plot displays a non-linear pattern.
  3. Normality (histogram, QQ plot, shapiro test). We can use visual cues to best infer normality. If our data is not perfectly normal, it is likely okay. We simply don't want to observe any patterns that don't let us assume this course of action.
  4. Homoscedasticity (goldfeldquandt test). To deal with hetersoscedasticity, we may have to identify the cause of a funnel-shapped pattern to a residual variance plot. This will only occur if our statisttical test provides a p-value < 0.05.

Multicollinearity Checks / Resolution Processes¶

  • VIF score 1-5 good
  • VIF score 5-10 moderate collinearity -VIF score 10+ high collinearity
In [56]:
#create function to check VIF

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor


def checking_vif(predictors):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # calculate VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]
    return vif

In [58]:
#create a loop for dropping and checking

def treating_multicollinearity(predictors, target, high_vif_columns):
  '''
  this function will analyze the effect of dropping columns with high VIF.
  This is analysis will be viewed from Adj. R squared and the RMSE.

  Inputs:
  predictors are our independent variables
  target is our dependent variable (rating)
  high_vif_columns are the ones we viewed previously, may be shown to drop using this function
  '''
  #empty lists to store analysis outcomes
  adj_r2 = []
  rmse = []

  #build OLS models by dropping one high VIF column
  #store the adj r sq and rMSE
  for cols in high_vif_columns:
    #defining the new train set
    train = predictors.loc[:, ~predictors.columns.str.startswith(cols)]
    #create model
    olsmodel_check = sm.OLS(target, train).fit()
    #add analysis outcomes to our empty lists
    adj_r2.append(olsmodel_check.rsquared_adj)
    rmse.append(np.sqrt(olsmodel_check.mse_resid))

  #creat dataframe for the results
  temp = pd.DataFrame({'col': high_vif_columns, 'Adj. R-Squared after dropping col': adj_r2, 'RMSE after dropping col': rmse}).sort_values(by='Adj. R-Squared after dropping col', ascending=False)
  temp.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
  return temp

In [62]:
# now we can focus on high p values of independent variables
# initial list of columns aka predictor/indepdendent variables
predictors = x_train2.copy()
cols = predictors.columns.tolist()

# setting an initial max p-value
max_p_value = 1

while len(cols) > 0:
    # defining the train set
    x_train_aux = predictors[cols]

    # fitting the model
    model = sm.OLS(y_train, x_train_aux).fit()

    # getting the p-values and the maximum p-value
    p_values = model.pvalues
    max_p_value = max(p_values)

    # name of the variable with maximum p-value
    feature_with_p_max = p_values.idxmax()

    if max_p_value > 0.05:
        cols.remove(feature_with_p_max)
    else:
        break

selected_features = cols
print(selected_features)

So far the tails of our curve are not perfectly normal; this is proven by a p-value < 0.05 in our Shapiro test. However, we are not seeing an intense pattern of something like Chi-Square, Bimodal, Exponential, Log/Power distribtuions of our Residuals.

  • This allows us to hold an assumption of normality, as there is not an alternate distribution that would better explain our data.

Homoscedasticity Check¶

We desire to obtain a p-value greater than 0.05 to meet the Homoscedastistic Assumption.

In [72]:
#import required tests
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(df_predictions["Residuals"], x_train3)
lzip(name, test)
Out[72]:
[('F statistic', 1.0648757500800878), ('p-value', 0.13825250199575034)]

With a p-value of ~0.138, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. We can say the residuals of our data are homoscedastic.

All Linear Regression Assumptions have been met.

Interpretation of Regression Results:

  1. Adjusted. R-squared: It reflects the fit of the model.
    • the value for adj. R-squared is approximately 0.84, which is a strong value.
    • do to our many assumption checks and resolution of multi-collinearity, we do not have concerns of over-fitting.
  1. const coefficient: Y-intercept of regression equation.
    • the value for const coefficient is 1.2451
    • this represents the starting value of normalized_used_price in Euros.
  1. Coefficient of a predictor variable: It represents the change in the output Y due to a change in a given predictor variable
    • Example: the coefficient of normalized_new_price is 0.4255. This tells us that the more expensive the cell phone was when it was first sold, the more value we will see for its normalized_used_price.
    • Example: the coefficient of years_old is -0.019. This tells us that the older a phone is, the less value it grants towards normalized_new_price.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

-

  1. The model is able to explain ~84% of the variation in the train & test data and within ~4.5% of the normalized_used_price on the test data, which is good.
    • This indicates that the model is good for prediction as well as inference purposes.

  2. If the normalized_new_price (original price of phone) increases by one unit, then its used_price increases by 0.4244 units, with all other variables held constant.

  3. If the number of years_old (age) increases by one unit, then its used_price will decrease by 0.019, with all other variables held constant.

  4. With a majority of ReCell's inventory being phones aged 5-8 years old, we can see that older phones do not have a higher value.

    • Recommendation: ReCell increase their inventory of of newer/modern phones with desireable technology .
    • Recommendation: ReCell implement a loyalty/buy-in program to returning customers that turn in their phone every 1-2 years in exchange for a discount.

  5. With a coefficient of 0.036 4G phones are not as popular as 5G phones.

    • Recommendation: ReCell focus their inventory on gathering 5G phones.

  6. Recommendation: ReCell can gather more data about their where their inventory is being obtained from; who is choosing to sell their used devices? Is it all over Europe, or a hot-spot country? Next, ReCell should investigate who is buying their products; are they shipping these used devices far? Can ReCell tap into the location of their inventory and try to sell close to the source?

    • We can further aid ReCell to stategize the geographical aspects of this data when it comes to shipping and pricing devices!
